 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Plain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Plasnes in Eure.","French: from Old French <i>plain</i>, an adjective meaning ‘flat’ and a noun meaning ‘plain’, hence a topographic name denoting e.g. a dwelling on a flat terrain. Compare   Duplain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Duplain","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Alderney): topographic name from Old French <i>plain</i>, an adjective meaning ‘flat’ and a noun meaning ‘plain’, with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’. Compare   Plain   2."]},{"name":"Plane","meanings":["English and French: variant of   Plain  ."]}]},{"name":"und","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Myer.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Pfund</i> ‘pound’, either a nickname or one of the names chosen at random from vocabulary words in the 18th and 19th centuries by government officials at the time when surnames became compulsory.","Altered form of German   Pfund  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pfund","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Claus, Erwin, Gerhard.","German: metonymic occupational name for a sealer of weights, or for a wholesale merchant, from Middle High German <i>pfunt</i> ‘pound’ (as a measure of weight and a unit of currency), or a nickname relating to a tax obligation."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes von Plain und Hardegg was born about 1193, in Austria as the daughter of * Konrad II von PLAIN-HARDEGG and Euphemia von ORTENBURG. She married Heinrich von Pfannberg. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died after 1298."},"et":{"um 1193–Aft 1298":"umbes 1193–pärast 1298","1193–1298":"1193–1298","1191–1282":"1191–1282","1229–1315":"1229–1315","1236–1318":"1236–1318","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Surnud","Aft 1298":"pärast 1298","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1193":"1193","1191":"1191","um 1193":"umbes 1193","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","<1229>":"1229","1298":"1298","Aft 1282":"pärast 1282","1318":"1318","um 1236":"umbes 1236","1229":"1229","Österreich":"Austria","<Of, Sannegg, Steiermark, Austria>":"Steiermark, Austria"},"fi":{"um 1193–Aft 1298":"noin 1193–1298 jälkeen","1193–1298":"1193–1298","1191–1282":"1191–1282","1229–1315":"1229–1315","1236–1318":"1236–1318","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Kuollut","Aft 1298":"1298 jälkeen","1260":"1260","1282":"1282","1193":"1193","1191":"1191","um 1193":"noin 1193","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","<1229>":"1229","1298":"1298","Aft 1282":"1282 jälkeen","1318":"1318","um 1236":"noin 1236","1229":"1229","Österreich":"Itäv